 <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-18811">
    <div id="comment-18811">
    <div class="comment-left">
    <div class="comment-author vcard">
    <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/292ca76caed5eece3547ca270ff66c4c?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /><cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.adsurdity.blogspot.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>ML Harris</a></cite></div><div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.mint.com/blog/saving/the-no-excuses-take-your-lunch-to-work-guide/comment-page-1/#comment-18811">1473 days ago</a></div>
    </div>
    <div class="comment-right"><p>Get a fun lunchbox. Something you like. I got a cool box from Japan. It makes me feel a wee bit cool to bring lunch from home. If you&#8217;re saving 1000-1500 a year, what&#8217;s my $30 lunch box, amortized over 50 weeks? </p>
<p>Make extra at dinner. It helps with the leftover aspect. </p>
<p>On save money at work: Don&#8217;t decorate your cube. It&#8217;s not really yours, and you&#8217;re blowing money on it. If you must make it homey, print stuff out (on the company color printer if you can) and call it a day.
